# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2026-united-states-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The **119th United States Congress** is the current meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened on January 3, 2025, for the last 17 days of Joe Biden's presidency and continued during the first two years of Donald Trump's second presidency.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Following the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained its slim majority in the House of Representatives (albeit with losing two net seats to end up with a three-seat majority).
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Republican Party also won a three-seat majority in the Senate after winning four net seats.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Upon Trump's second inauguration on January 20, 2025, the Republican Party has an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 115th Congress (2017–2019), which was in session during Trump's first term.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The 119th Congress features the slimmest majority in the House for any party since the 72nd Congress (1931–1933), and the first openly transgender member of Congress in history, Representative Sarah McBride (D-DE).
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It also features the fewest split Senate delegations since the passage of the Seventeenth Amendment, which established the direct election of U.S. senators.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Despite a trifecta, the first year of the Congress saw the lowest number of House votes in a nonelection year since the 101st Congress in 1990.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained control of the House of Representatives and gained control of the Senate, while Republican nominee Donald Trump won the presidential election, securing a second non-consecutive term.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The results of the election were attributed to economic conditions of voters and concerns over immigration, particularly the Mexico–United States border crisis.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Senate flipped to a 53–47 Republican majority, and in their leadership elections, Senator John Thune of South Dakota was elected to succeed Mitch McConnell, who had been in power for 18 years.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The House assumed a 220–215 Republican majority, among the narrowest controlling majorities in House history with the 65th Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Mike Johnson was re-elected as speaker on the first ballot after initially not receiving enough votes on the roll call, with the vote remaining open until enough members changed votes to support him.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] On January 6, a joint session convened to count the presidential Electoral College votes.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The proceedings were peaceful, four years after the January 6 Capitol attack, in which supporters of Trump entered the Capitol and disrupted Joe Biden's certification as president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In response to the attack and Trump's efforts to overturn the 2020 election, Congress has passed revisions to the Electoral Count Act that prevent the vice president from altering the results and significantly raises the bar for certification objections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All class 1 seats were contested in the November 2024 elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In this Congress, class 1 means their term commenced in the current Congress, requiring re-election in 2030; class 2 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2026; and class 3 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2028.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All seats were filled by election in November 2024, or special elections thereafter as noted below.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/120th-united-states-congress] This is a list of the several United States Congresses, since their beginning in 1789, including their beginnings, endings, and the dates of their individual sessions.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/120th-united-states-congress] Each elected bicameral Congress (of the two chambers of the Senate and the House of Representatives) lasts for two years and begins on January 3 of odd-numbered years.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] The first midterm elections were held in the United States in 1790 and 1791.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] They occurred in the middle of President George Washington's first term, and determined the members of the 2nd United States Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Formal political parties did not exist, but Congress was broadly divided between a faction supporting the policies of the Washington administration and a faction opposed to those policies.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Despite modest gains for the anti-administration faction, the pro-administration faction retained control of both houses of Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Vermont and Kentucky joined the union during the 2nd Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the House, neither faction made significant gains or losses, and the pro-administration faction retained control of the chamber.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the anti-administration faction picked up a moderate number of seats, but the pro-administration faction narrowly retained control of the chamber.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 3rd United States Congress, in 1792 and 1793.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Congress was broadly divided between a Pro-Administration faction supporting the policies of George Washington's administration and an Anti-Administration faction opposed to those policies.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Due to this, the Federalist Party (generally overlapping with the Pro-Administration faction) and the Democratic-Republican Party (generally overlapping with the Anti-Administration faction) were starting to emerge as the distinct political parties of the First Party System.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In this election, the Pro-Administration faction maintained control of the Senate, but lost its majority in the House.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, incumbent President George Washington was re-elected without any major opposition.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington had considered retirement, but was convinced to seek re-election for the purpose of national unity.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Though Washington went unchallenged, Governor George Clinton of New York sought to unseat John Adams as vice president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Adams received the second most electoral votes, and so was re-elected to office.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the House, 37 seats were added following the 1790 census.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction picked up several seats, narrowly taking the majority from the Pro-Administration faction.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Frederick Muhlenberg, who leaned closer to the Pro-Administration faction, was elected Speaker of the House.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Anti-Administration faction picked up one seat, but the Pro-Administration faction maintained a small majority.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Elections occurred in the middle of President George Washington's second term.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Members of the 4th United States Congress were chosen in this election.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Tennessee was admitted as a state during the 4th Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] The election took place at the beginning of the First Party System, with the Democratic-Republican Party and Federalist Party emerging as political parties, succeeding the anti-administration faction and the pro-administration faction.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the House, the Democratic-Republicans picked up a small number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] However, Federalist Jonathan Dayton was elected Speaker of the House, defeating Frederick Muhlenberg, who had a less clear partisan affiliation.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Federalists picked up a moderate number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 5th United States Congress, in 1796 and 1797.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The election took place during the beginning stages of the First Party System, as the Federalist Party and the Democratic-Republican Party clashed over the states' rights, the financial policies of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton, and the recently ratified Jay Treaty.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The Federalists maintained control of the Senate, and won control of the House and the presidency.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the first contested presidential election and the first presidential election in which parties played a major role, Federalist Vice President John Adams narrowly defeated Democratic-Republican former Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams won New England while Jefferson won the South, leaving the mid-Atlantic states to decide the election.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] As the election took place prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, Jefferson, who finished with the second most electoral votes, succeeded Adams as vice president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Federalist former Governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina finished with the third most electoral votes, while Democratic-Republican Senator Aaron Burr of New York finished in fourth place.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] This election marked the only time in American history that members of two different political parties were elected as president and vice president.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams's election made him the first member of a political party to be elected president, as George Washington had remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the House, Federalists won moderate gains, taking majority control of the chamber.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the Senate, Federalists picked up one seat, maintaining a commanding majority in the chamber.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The **2026 United States elections** are scheduled to be held, in large part, on November 3, 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] In these midterm elections, scheduled to occur during Republican president Donald Trump's nonconsecutive second term, all 435 seats in the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives and 35 of the 100 seats in the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Senate will be contested to determine the 120th United States Congress.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 39 state and territorial U.S. gubernatorial elections, attorney general elections, and numerous state and local elections, will also be contested.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Election experts and Democratic officials have characterized the investigations as efforts to intimidate election officials and voters ahead of the midterms, while the Justice Department has said the searches were court-authorized.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The second Trump administration has imposed tariffs on much of the world with the intent to re-industrialize America, a decision that received mixed reception.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] It was criticized by experts and global leaders for worsening inflation rather than fighting it.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The administration's immigration policies, including deportations by ICE due to strengthened funding via the One Big Beautiful Bill Act, were also scrutinized by experts and activists.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The outbreak of the 2026 Iran war on February 28 introduced a further complicating factor, with rising gasoline prices emerging as a central electoral concern.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The 2026 elections will be the first federal elections since the 2016 presidential contest where ABC News, CNN, CBS News, NBC News, the Associated Press and Fox News will use one election survey, the Voter Poll by SSRS, to measure voters' opinions and preferences.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] From 2018 to 2024, the former four news networks continued to use data from the National Election Pool while the Associated Press and Fox News relied on AP VoteCast.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Although Trump will not be listed as a candidate on any state ballot in 2026, voters' views of his presidency will likely be a factor in the election.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] During the 2025 off year elections, exit polls found that many voted in opposition to Trump or said that he was not a factor.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Surveys released in late 2025 and early 2026 find that many view Trump's handling of the economy and immigration, two issues that propelled him to victory in the 2024 election, negatively.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] During elections held in his first term, Trump was on the minds of many who voted.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The Republican Party performed worse than expected in the November 2025 general elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Democratic candidates Abigail Spanberger of Virginia and Mikie Sherrill of New Jersey won their gubernatorial races over their Republican opponents by larger than expected margins.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats performed strongly in the concurrent state legislative elections, winning a supermajority in the New Jersey General Assembly and expanding their majority in the Virginia House of Delegates.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] In New York City, Democrat Zohran Mamdani, a self-identified democratic socialist, was elected mayor in a three-way race against independent former governor Andrew Cuomo and Republican Curtis Sliwa.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The main theme of the elections was the United States affordability crisis.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Trump floated the idea of canceling the elections, citing an expected loss in the elections and a distrust in democratic systems.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt later claimed Trump was "speaking facetiously", and was "simply joking".
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] In February, Trump stated that the elections should be nationalized to prevent voter fraud.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] A day later, Steve Bannon said the federal government was planning to send ICE to patrol polling stations in an attempt to prevent a Democratic victory, vowing to "never again allow an election to be stolen".
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] That month, the House of Representatives passed the SAVE America Act, an amended version of the previously proposed Safeguard American Voter Eligibility Act.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The bill, if approved by the Senate and signed into law by Trump, would've required registering voters to provide proof of citizenship in order to obtain or renew their voter registration.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Voting rights activists alleged that such provisions would disenfranchise married women, racial minorities, low-income groups, and people who legally changed their name, among others.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The bill ultimately died in the Senate that June, with four Republicans joining Democrats to block its inclusion.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] On February 27, *The Washington Post* reported that several right-wing activists are working with the Trump administration to draft an executive order which, if signed, would effectively instate a national emergency and give Trump extended powers over the elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Trump denied the existence of the executive order.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The Justice Department also demanded voter registration data from states, suing 23 states and the District of Columbia that declined to provide unredacted voter rolls; all of the sued states were led by Democrats or had been won by Joe Biden in 2020.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] In March, Stateline reported that legislation to "restrict immigration enforcement or the presence of federal forces" near polling places and other election sites has been offered or announced in California, Connecticut, New Mexico, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Virginia and Washington.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The same month, the Associated Press reported that several Democratic-led states including New Mexico and Virginia are taking steps to counter potential tactics to intimidate voters.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] In May, Ned Lamont, the governor of Connecticut, signed into law a bill that restricts immigration enforcement at locations including schools and places of worship.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The legislation also prohibits law enforcement from wearing facial coverings or personal disguises.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Analysts had predicted that a decision in *Callais* reducing the scope of the VRA could allow Republicans to gain a significant number of seats in the U.S.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives from redistricting in the Southeast, where the VRA has generally prevented Republican-controlled legislatures from maximizing their numbers of "safe" districts.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] *The New York Times* estimated that, if the Court weakened the VRA, up to twelve seats could shift from Democratic to Republican control.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] When the decision in *Callais* was announced, media outlets characterized it as a "landmark" decision, predicting that the additional restrictions on Section 2 of the VRA will likely make challenges to redistricting significantly more difficult.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Analysts expect it will allow southern states to eliminate majority-minority districts, a development that would amplify the Republican party's representation in Congress and lead to the effective disenfranchisement of numerous voters.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The decision was seen by legal scholars as a culmination of Roberts' efforts to weaken the VRA since he came on the bench, while media outlets considered the decision as rendering the VRA all but dead and harming the country's democratic process.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Other commentators considered the ruling to start a new era of Jim Crow laws, allowing for legal discrimination of minorities.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The court's opinion was expected to affect all levels of government including state and local governments.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] An analysis from *The Guardian* found that Justice Alito's claim that Black voter turnout had surpassed white voter turnout in two of the five most recent presidential elections, both nationally and in Louisiana, was based on misleading data and questionable methodology.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Holder* which struck down the preclearance formula defined in Section 4(b) of the VRA for states with historical discrimination concerns including Louisiana.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 35 seats in the United States Senate will be up for election, including all 33 Class 2 seats.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans gained majority control of the Senate in the 2024 elections by flipping four Democratic seats.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Two Democratic-held seats, Georgia and Michigan, are in states won by Donald Trump in the previous presidential election, while Maine is the only Republican-held seat in a state won by Kamala Harris.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] All 435 voting seats in the United States House of Representatives will be up for election.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Additionally, elections will be held to select the non-voting delegate for the District of Columbia and the non-voting delegates from 4 of the 5 U.S. territories, excluding Puerto Rico due to its non-voting delegate serving a 4 year term.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] There are 16 Democratic incumbents in districts Donald Trump won, while only 8 Republican incumbents are in seats won by Harris.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The House map features a number of new congressional maps: Ohio and Utah will have new, court-mandated congressional districts this cycle; Missouri, North Carolina, and Texas redrew their maps mid-cycle; and the district map was changed in California following the passage of Prop 50.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] At least seven special elections to the House of Representatives were or will be held in 2026.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 36 states and three territories will be holding regularly scheduled gubernatorial elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] The governors of 15 states and two territories will be term-limited.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Nine states will be holding regularly scheduled lieutenant gubernatorial elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 30 states, two territories, and one federal district will be holding regularly scheduled attorney general elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 26 states will be holding regularly scheduled secretary of state elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 27 states will be holding regularly scheduled treasurer elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 23 states will be holding regularly scheduled auditor elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 88 state legislative chambers and 5 territorial chambers will be holding regularly scheduled elections.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] Elections are scheduled to be held in 2026, in various states across the country, including supreme courts and appellate courts.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] 100 ballot measures in 37 states will be held in the November election.
[src:2026-united-states-elections/2026-united-states-elections-p01] A number of major cities will hold mayoral elections in 2026.
